1 Overview
**********

‘johnson’ is a multi-format dictionary UI for Emacs.  It
provides the functionality of programs such as GoldenDict and StarDict,
allowing you to look up words across multiple dictionaries
simultaneously
and view formatted definitions in a dedicated Emacs buffer.

   The package is implemented entirely in Emacs Lisp with no external
dependencies, relying on Emacs 30.1's built-in sqlite support for
efficient headword indexing.  Dictionary files are parsed natively,
without calling external tools.

   In version 0.4, the package supports the DSL (ABBYY Lingvo),
StarDict, MDict, and BGL (Babylon) formats, including
dictzip-compressed files (‘.dsl.dz’ and ‘.dict.dz’) and
encrypted MDict files.  It also provides a DICT protocol client
(RFC 2229) for querying remote dictionary servers.

   The architecture is modular.  The core module (‘johnson.el’) provides

the lookup engine, results buffer, navigation, history, and a
plist-based format registry (*note Format registration::).
The sqlite index management is delegated to ‘johnson-db.el’, which
maintains one database per dictionary file in a configurable cache
directory (*note Cache directory::).  Shared infrastructure
for dictzip decompression lives in ‘johnson-dictzip.el’.  Each
dictionary format is handled by a separate backend
module--‘johnson-dsl.el’, ‘johnson-stardict.el’,
‘johnson-mdict.el’, ‘johnson-bgl.el’, and
‘johnson-dict.el’--that registers itself with the core via the
format registry.

   A typical workflow consists of three steps.  First, configure
‘johnson-dictionary-directories’ to point at your dictionary files
(*note Dictionary discovery::).  Second, run ‘M-x johnson-index’ to scan

and index all discovered dictionaries (*note Indexing dictionaries::).
Third, use ‘M-x johnson-lookup’ to look up words with dynamic
completion (*note Looking up words::).

   Here is a sample configuration using ‘elpaca’ and ‘use-package’:

     (use-package johnson
       :ensure (:host github :repo "benthamite/johnson")
       :custom
       (johnson-dictionary-directories '("~/dictionaries/"))
       (johnson-default-search-scope 'all)
       (johnson-dictionary-priorities '(("Oxford English-Spanish" . -10)
                                        ("Collins English-Spanish" . -5)))
       (johnson-history-max 200)
       (johnson-history-persist t)
       (johnson-display-images t)
       :bind
       ("C-c d" . johnson-lookup))

   Results are displayed in a ‘*johnson*’ buffer using ‘johnson-mode’, a

read-only major mode derived from ‘special-mode’.  Each dictionary that
contains a match for the queried word gets its own collapsible section,
displayed in priority order (*note Display ordering::).  The buffer
supports Info-like navigation: press ‘n’ and ‘p’ to move between
sections, ‘TAB’ to collapse or expand a section, ‘RET’ to follow
cross-references, ‘l’ and ‘r’ to navigate back and forward through
lookup history, ‘I’ to toggle inline images, ‘S’ to search within
definitions, ‘b’ to bookmark an entry, ‘M’ to remove a bookmark, and
‘H’ to browse the full lookup history.

   Dictionaries are organized into groups by language pair
(e.g., "English → Spanish").  Groups are auto-detected from dictionary
metadata but can be customized via ‘johnson-dictionary-groups’
(*note Search scope and groups::).

   The package also provides a dictionary list buffer via ‘M-x
johnson-list-dictionaries’, showing all discovered dictionaries with
their indexing status and entry counts
(*note Dictionary list::).


